 width="300"></td></tr></table></p>
           
            <p style="text-align: justify;" class="intertitre">Khroskyabs is a language of the Rgyalrongic group of the Trans-Himalayan (a.k.a. Sino-Tibetan) family, spoken in the Chuchen and Dzamthang districts, as well as in the city of Barkhams, Sichuan, China. It is an SOV language with an elaborate phonological system and a polysynthetic verbal morphology.</p>
            <p style="text-align: justify;" class="intertitre">Khroskyabs is, of all Trans-Himalayan languages currently known to science, the one with the largest inventory of initial consonant clusters. The Wobzi dialect, in particular, has 715 different clusters (Lai 2017: 100), of which the most elaborate has no less than five consecutive consonants: ʁɴzbrɑ́ 'to dare (generic)'.</p>
            <p style="text-align: justify;" class="intertitre">With regard to verbal morphology, Khroskyabs has a mainly prefixing gabaritic morphology. Personal indexing is hierarchical with reverse marking: thus, a transitive verb indexes information from two participants. Derivational morphology is replete with morpho-phonological processes. A salient example is found in variations on the causative prefix s- according to its phonological context: kʰɑ̂ 'to give' → s-kʰɑ̂ 'to cause to give', gí 'to dress' → z-gí 'to cause to dress', ʁbɑ́ɣ 'to explode, to burst' → ʁ&lt;z&gt;bɑ́ɣ 'to cause to burst', vzɑ́r 'to be spicy' → l-zɑv 'to spice up, to cause to get spicy', and so on (Lai 2016).</p>
            <p style="text-align: justify;" class="intertitre">In addition to its conservative features, which facilitate comparative Trans-Himalayan diachronic linguistic study, Khroskyabs also has innovative phenomena that are typologically rare (or even unique in the present state of the art in linguistics). It is therefore an important language both within its family and from the perspective of general linguistics. Unfortunately, most of the dialects of Khroskyabs are not yet sufficiently documented. I would like to avail myself of the present opportunity to reach out to everyone who may be interested to join us to improve this key area of documentation and research. Please do feel free to get in touch.</p>
            <p class="intertitre" align="left">&nbsp;</p>
            <p>Bibliography:</p>
